metadata.name: Tendencies #6
metadata.description:
Tendencies is the first in a set of collections based on a month-long study of Edward Zajec, one of the early pioneers of generative art in the 1970s.

Zajec's generative work was motivated by redundancy in his paintings: "The monotony of the manual task and the limited number of variations which I was able to produce in a given time made me realize the inadequacy of traditional methods in dealing with our present reality." Tendencies was inspired by ‚Äî and pays tribute to ‚Äî one if Zajec's earliest forays into generative creation: a work titled RAM 10 V.15, which was written on an IBM 1620 and programmed in FORTRAN.

The title of the collection itself is a reference to the first exhibition of Zajec's RAM series, while the number of editions minted referencing the year Zajec put plotter to paper.

Made in p5js
Created December 2022
By @christine_hall

metadata.name: Tema #15
metadata.description:
Tema is the second in a set of collections based on a month-long study of Edward Zajec, one of the early pioneers of generative art in the 1970s.

After gaining some traction with his original collection RAM, Zajec and his collaborating programmer Matjaz Hmeljak undertook a more complex algorithm titled "The Cube: Theme and Variation" (or TVC). The program laid out 8 unique elements in a grid, creating a three-dimensional viewing of objects in space. They published a paper about the underlying algorithm, found at: http://www.edwardzajec.com/tvc4/pil1/index.html

TVC was first printed in 1971, shortly after Zajec returned to Italy following his artistic studies in the US. It was programmed on an IBM 9044 & printed with a CalComp 563 plotter.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save a high-resolution version of the image

Made in p5js
Created January 2023
By @christine_hall

metadata.name: Nebula, Solitude #17
metadata.description:
Nebula is one of the most magnificent stellar phenomena to behold. It is a distinct luminescent part of the interstellar medium, which consists of ionized gas and cosmic dust. Nebulae are often star-forming regions, where stars are born in solitude but surrounded by beautiful light and matter.

In this series, I continue the exploration of color and gravity, the effect of mass on speed, the effect of speed on hue, and how light can change by passing through big particles and dust systems.

I also want to let you participate in the creation of your artwork variation too. Each iteration is a unique and unpredictable dance of light in the dust and gravitation between matter clusters, however,  with the controls listed below, you can change the probability of light/dust blocks as well as the tiling layout.

[L] - create a new layout
[S] - reshuffle the current layout

[Shift] + [1] - change dust blocks probability to 0.0 and reshuffle the current layout
[Shift] + [2] - ‚Äî//‚Äî 0.2
[Shift] + [3] - ‚Äî//‚Äî 0.4
[Shift] + [4] - ‚Äî//‚Äî 0.6
[Shift] + [5] - ‚Äî//‚Äî 0.8
[Shift] + [6] - ‚Äî//‚Äî 1.0

Basics:
[A] - skip/restart the animation

[1] - save PNG in low resolution
[2] - save PNG in medium resolution
[3] - save PNG in high resolution
[4] - save PNG in ultra-high resolution

Experimental zone:
[E] - toggle endless animation
[0] - save the current frame in low resolution

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.

Use Chrome 107 for the best experience, other browsers are significantly slower on this artwork, visual results also may vary.

Made with love and p5js

By Collapsar Beauty

metadata.description:
Change in nature comes as a smooth routine. The color change takes over the leaves until they fall off. And eventually green Will reappear.
It is not so for humans.
This collection looks up to nature and embraces change. At some point in life, an unexpected crisis may occur, yet it can bring new opportunities. Welcome the learning process. Embrace the growth. Face life and live.

metadata.name: Formes Bin√†ries #29
metadata.description:
"Formes Bin√†ries" (Binary Shapes) is a visualization and sonication of fxhash characters in binary code.
By default the result of the process is showed. 

you can see and listen how this final result was formed in two different ways:

SIMPLE MODE: 
Click/Touch to start.

FULL MODE:
Press any key / shake your device
(requires a large use of resources, recommended for computer)

BASICS:
-A concrete number of fxhash characters (8,16,24,32,40 or 48) are converted to binary from their ASCII code.
-A geometric shape and sound wave shape are randomly assigned: Circle+Sine Wave, Square+Square wave and Triangle+Triangle wave.
-Each bit with value '1' is visually represented with an assigned form, and 0 with nothing. Bits are represented concentrically, sequentially starting the fxhash binary string with the smallest shape, and increasing in size by each bit 1. These shapes are assigned a color according to the ASCII character to which the bit belongs bit
-The same is done with the sound part, the bits with value 1 are assigned a frequency according to the ASCII character to which they belong.

By default the result of the process is showed. 

you can see and listen how this final result was formed in two different ways:

SIMPLE MODE: 
Click/Touch to start.

FULL MODE:
Press any key / shake your device
(requires a large use of resources, recommended for computer)

Features: 

-num_chars: number of fxhash characters used (8,16,24,32,40 or 48).

-dark: black(true) or white (false) background.

-color: group of colors that are assigned to each ASCII character.

-one_thikness: all shapes has the same thikness (true) or not (false).

-shape: shape (+wave form of the sound) randomly assigned: circle, square or triangle.

-blur: value of blur.

-deviation: the shapes has a desviation on its position.

-freq_range: ran
NOTE: after a few days if 50% of mints have not been exceeded, the number of iterations will be halved.

metadata.name: Step by Step #181
metadata.description:
Step by Step explores the feeling of being stuck, confined - walking the path ahead of you often only seeing the immediate next step until exhaustion. We all feel this way from time to time ‚Äî in our lives, jobs, bodies, situations ‚Äî yet in our search for something, we shouldn't forget that there can still be beauty along the path.

The project takes some inspiration from Henri Matisse, both in the aesthetics of his later works (i.e. the "Cut Outs") and metaphorically in the sense that he had underwent medical treatment which left him wheelchair- or bed-bound towards the later part of his life, forcing him to give up painting, yet in his exploration of this new creative medium which involved cutting paper and pinning them up, his unorthodox work went on to become the most transformative of his career.

Released as part of the 4th edition of the Cure¬≥ Parkinson's cure fundraiser exhibition organized by Artwise Curators and Bonhams as part of a specially comissioned selection of generative artists minting NFTs, curated by Foteini Valeonti and Alex Estorick with the support of fx(hash) at Bonhams, London from 13-17th January 2023.
